of-world%2Funacceptable-japan-condemns-trumps-hiroshima-comparison-to-iran-strikes-demands-retraction%2Famp_articleshow%2F122109236.cms%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Why%20being%20a%20parent%20could%20give%20your%20career%20a%20boost%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%225779%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20baby%20crawls%20away%20from%20its%20mother%2C%20who%20is%20sitting%20on%20the%20floor%20looking%20at%20her%20cellphone.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F685be6a6f748d8c055f450aa%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%223852%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3E%C2%A0The%20%26quot%3Bmotherhood%20penalty%26quot%3B%20era%20may%20be%20over.%3Cp%3EElisa%20Schu%2Fpicture%20alliance%20via%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cul%3E%3Cli%3EA%20study%20found%20the%20%26quot%3Bmotherhood%20penalty%26quot%3B%20may%20be%20gone%20and%20that%20being%20a%20parent%20could%20aid%20your%20career.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EResearchers%20found%20a%20%26quot%3Bparenthood%20boost%2C%26quot%3B%20a%20tendency%20for%20people%20to%20evaluate%20parents%20more%20favorably%20than%20their%20childfree%20peers.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EOne%20of%20the%20researchers%20told%20BI%20that%20the%20findings%20were%20surprising.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20decades%2C%20research%20has%20warned%20of%20a%20%26quot%3B%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fstay-at-home-moms-open-up-about-the-motherhood-penalty-2022-2%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3Emotherhood%20penalty%3C%2Fa%3E%26quot%3B%20in%20the%20workplace%3A%20women%20who%20have%20children%20are%20sometimes%20viewed%20as%20less%20committed%20and%20less%20competent%2C%20diminishing%20their%20chances%20of%20promotions%20or%20raises.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20a%20new%20major%20study%20found%20the%20script%20may%20be%20outdated%20%E2%80%94%20and%20that%20parenthood%20may%20actually%20help%20some%20employees.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20paper%20published%20in%20the%20Journal%20of%20Experimental%20Social%20Psychology%20found%20no%20evidence%20of%20a%20motherhood%20penalty%20in%20a%20series%20of%20large-scale%20experiments.%20It%20was%20authored%20by%20Christopher%20D.%20Petsko%2C%20an%20assistant%20professor%20of%20organizational%20behavior%20at%20UNC%20Chapel%20Hill%3B%20Rebecca%20Ponce%20de%20Leon%2C%20an%20assistant%20professor%20at%20Columbia%20Business%20School%3B%20and%20Ashleigh%20Shelby%20Rosette%2C%20professor%20of%20leadership%20at%20Duke%20University's%20Fuqua%20School%20of%20Business.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EInstead%2C%20the%20researchers%20found%20what%20they%20called%20a%20%26quot%3Bparenthood%20boost%26quot%3B%20%E2%80%94%20a%20tendency%20for%20people%20to%20evaluate%20parents%20more%20favorably%20than%20their%20childfree%20peers%2C%20regardless%20of%20gender.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20was%20very%20surprised%2C%20yes%2C%26quot%3B%20Petsko%20told%20Business%20Insider%20about%20the%20findings.%20%26quot%3BThe%20motherhood%20penalty%20has%20been%20such%20a%20foundational%20finding%20in%20the%20behavioral%20sciences%20that%20seeing%20it%20not%20replicate%20was%20striking.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThat%20said%2C%20society%20has%20changed%20a%20lot%20over%20the%20last%20couple%20of%20decades%2C%20and%20it's%20not%20unusual%20for%20phenomena%20that%20were%20first%20documented%2020%20years%20ago%20to%20look%20different%20today.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22cf455d3f-f5d1-4e6d-a2cb-b7779b2cabe7%5C%22%3ENo%20penalty%2C%20but%20a%20boost%20for%20some%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20a%20series%20of%20four%20large-scale%20experiments%20with%204%2C742%20participants%2C%20Petsko's%20team%20revisited%20the%20classic%20motherhood%20penalty%20studies%20with%20a%20new%20lens%3A%20racial%20identity.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThey%20manipulated%20race%2C%20gender%2C%20and%20parental%20status%20in%20fictional%20employee%20profiles%20and%20asked%20participants%20to%20rate%20these%20employees'%20competence%2C%20warmth%2C%20and%20suitability%20for%20promotion.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ENot%20only%20did%20the%20researchers%20find%20no%20evidence%20of%20a%20penalty%20for%20mothers%2C%20they%20concluded%20that%20the%20opposite%20was%20true.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EParents%20were%20consistently%20rated%20more%20positively%20than%20non-parents%2C%20regardless%20of%20gender.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20there%20was%20a%20catch.%20While%20both%20Black%20and%20white%20parents%20received%20a%20boost%2C%20the%20increase%20was%20significantly%20larger%20for%20white%20employees.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20the%20researchers%20combined%20data%20from%20all%20four%20experiments%2C%20they%20found%20that%20white%20parents%20were%20perceived%20as%20more%20competent%20and%20warmer%20and%20were%20less%20likely%20to%20be%20discriminated%20against%20than%20their%20childless%20peers.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBlack%20parents%2C%20by%20contrast%2C%20didn't%20enjoy%20the%20same%20bump.%20In%20some%20cases%2C%20they%20saw%20no%20change%20in%20evaluation%20at%20all%20when%20parenthood%20was%20introduced.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BTruth%20be%20told%2C%20we're%20not%20sure%2C%26quot%3B%20Petsko%20said%20when%20asked%20why%20white%20parents%20seemed%20to%20benefit%20more.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BSomething%20that%20seems%20plausible%20%E2%80%94%20at%20least%20to%20me%20%E2%80%94%20is%20that%20the%20societal%20prescription%20to%20'raise%20a%20family'%20might%20be%20something%20that%20people%20hold%20more%20strongly%20for%20members%20of%20dominant%20racial%20groups%20than%20for%20members%20of%20non-dominant%20racial%20groups%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BAnd%20if%20that's%20the%20case%2C%20then%20it%20would%20make%20sense%20for%20people%20in%20the%20US%20to%20more%20strongly%20reward%20parenthood%20when%20they%20see%20it%20in%20white%20employees%20than%20when%20they%20see%20it%20in%20Black%20employees.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20Petsko%20said%20his%20comments%20were%20purely%20%26quot%3Bspeculation%26quot%3B%20and%20that%20there%20was%20no%20data%20to%20help%20determine%20the%20causes%20of%20this%20racial%20bias.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%2282b87225-8440-4208-b243-19f38842ae68%5C%22%3ENot%20over%20yet%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EPetsko%20said%20he%20did%20not%20want%20companies%20to%20conclude%20that%20the%20findings%20meant%20that%20motherhood%20penalties%20were%20now%20%26quot%3Ba%20thing%20of%20the%20past.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BAlthough%20motherhood%20penalties%20didn't%20emerge%20in%20our%20experiments%20%E2%80%94%20which%20assessed%20single-shot%20impressions%20of%20men%20versus%20women%20in%20the%20workplace%20%E2%80%94%20they%20do%20still%20seem%20to%20emerge%20in%20other%20kinds%20of%20studies%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said%2C%20citing%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwomen-pay-gap-motherhood-fatherhood-nobel-prize-harvard-economist-2023-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3Elongitudinal%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ffailed-working-mothers-how-to-build-better-workplaces-policies-2021-1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3Estudies%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20men's%20versus%20women's%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fmen-earn-more-money-after-having-a-kid-2014-9%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3Ewages%3C%2Fa%3E%20after%20they%20become%20parents.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EInstead%2C%20Petsko%20said%20parenthood%20itself%20may%20trigger%20biased%20evaluations.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThere%20truly%20may%20be%20a%20systematic%20tendency%20to%20think%20of%20someone%20as%20more%20competent%20at%20their%20jobs%2C%20and%20even%20as%20more%20deserving%20of%20promotion%2C%20simply%20because%20we've%20learned%20that%20they%20have%20children%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BAnd%20if%20that%20bias%20is%20real%20%E2%80%94%20and%20not%20just%20real%2C%20but%20directed%20more%20strongly%20toward%20white%20employees%20than%20toward%20Black%20employees%20%E2%80%94%20then%20companies%20ought%20to%20know%20about%20it.%20Compan